    <title>I wish the B/X and OD&amp;D retro-clones had added a "Saving Throw" entry for spells</title>
    <id>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2021/07/23/i-wish-the-bx-and-odd-retro-clones-had-added-a-saving-throw-entry-for-spells/</id>
    <updated>2021-07-23T04:08:53-04:00</updated>
    <published>2021-07-23T04:08:53-04:00</published>
    <author>
      <name>T. Kurt Bond</name>
    </author>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2021/07/23/i-wish-the-bx-and-odd-retro-clones-had-added-a-saving-throw-entry-for-spells/"/>
    <summary type="html">&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;One simple improvement on B/X D&amp;amp;D and OD&amp;amp;D that wouldn't have been a
change in the rules, just a change in presentation, that I'd wished
that the B/X and OD&amp;amp;D retro-clones had made was adding a “Saving
Throw” entry to their spell descriptions was like that of AD&amp;amp;D.  Basic
Fantasy, Labyrinth Lord/Advanced Edition Companion, Old-School
Essentials, and Sword &amp;amp; Wizardry Complete and Core all fail to do
this.  As it is, you have to read the spell description to figure out
if a saving throw is allowed and what it means.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I'm &lt;strong&gt;really&lt;/strong&gt; surprised that Old-School Essentials didn't do this,
with all its other improvements to the presentation of B/X style
games.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Oh well.  Maybe OSE will add it in a later edition.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</summary>
